{"/service/ndnp/mthi/batch_mthi_bison_ver01/data/sn83045217/00295860728/1921011501/0016.xml":{"full_text":"NAMED BY\nEvery Member of Old Board on List of Nominees\nIs Re-Elected; Annual Reports\nHeard; Work Planned.\nTwenty director of the Great Falls\nCommercial club for 1921 were elected\nat the annual meeting of the members\nin the palm room of the Hotel Rainbow\nFriday night. A feature >f the election\nwas that ten of the members of the\nretiring board nominated, all were re\nelected. The membership of the board\nwag increased from 19 to 20 because of\na tie vote between Harry Newman and\nF: E. Beatty. Each will have a half\nvote until some other members retire\nfrom the board for any reason.\nThe new directors are:\nF. E. Beaty, manager State Life In\nsurance company.\nW. A. Bertke, manager Great Falls\nGas company.\nA. ,T. Breitenstein, manager Hotel\nHainbow.\nFrank Brown, vice president Great\nFalls Meat company.\nL. L. Callaway, attorney.\nClarence Conrad, Conrad Grocery\ncompany.\nFred Fligman, president Paris Dry\nGoods company.\nS. S. Ford, vice president Great Falls\nNational bank.\nW. II. George, president, W. II.\nGeorge company.\nF. J. Gies, president F. J. Gies com\npany.\nGeorge Grover, proprietor Great\nFalls Monumental works.\nA. 1*. Ileaney, state distributor Velie\nagency.\nJ. R. Ilobbins, manager Montana\nPower company.\nN. T. Lease, Lease Richards, con\ntractors.\nHarry Newman, real estate.\nR. B. Noble, vice president and man\nager Commercial National bank.\nJ. W. Sherwood, vice president and\nmanager Royal Milling company.\n\u25a0Saui Stephenson, president Great\nFalls Townsite company.\nO. S. Warden, manager Great Falls\nTribune.\nD. K. Woods, physician and surgeon.\nElect Officers Tuesday.\nThe new board of directors will meet\nnext Tuesday at 4 p. m. in the Com\nmercial club office in the First National\nbank building to choose officers of the\nclub for the coming year. The offic\ners to be chosen are president, first\nvice president, secretary and treasurer.\nTotal receipts by the Commercial\nclub durinjr 1920 were .$13,758, accord\ning to the report of Treasurer W. A\nBrown. On hand at the beginning of\nthe year was .$1,079. Expenditures\nduring the year totaled .$14,2(58, leav\ning a balance in the club treasury of\n$571 on January 1, 1921.\nFollowing the casting of the vote\ntalks were made by several members\nof the club on the work of the organi\nzation during the last year and on\nthe business outlook for Great Falls\nand the nearby communities.\nTheodore Gibson Talks.\nThe first talk was made Theodore\nGibson, son of the late Senator Gib\nson, fonnder of Great Falls. Mr. (Jib\nson advocated action by the Commercial\nclub to get closer co-operation between\nthe city council and the park board\nwith the ultimate aim of securing ade\ncji^tc water supply for the parks here.\nThe city's parks, Mr. Gibson said, had\nbeen his father's greatest delight and\nhis aim had been to build them to the\ngreatest possible extent.\nJulius Peters, attorney here, and\npresident of the Ilomestake Oil com\npany with large holdings in the Cat\nCreek district, gave a talk on the great\nfuture for Montana in the oil fields,\nlie exhorted the Commercial club men\nTalcum\nIs so soothing and cooling for\nbaby's tender skin after a bath\nwith Cuticura Soap.\nBaaipU Zfteb Trm by Mail. Address: \"Cntlc\u00abraL*l\n4t, Mats Sold ev\u00abry\nwhere. Soap 26c. Oint ment 25 and toe. Talcum 25c.\nMTCaticura Soap ahaeea without mag.\nHUMPHREYS'\nWITCH HAZEL 0INTMEN1\n(COMPOUND)\nFor Piles or Hemorrhoids,\nExternal or Internal, Blind or\nBleeding, Itching or Burning.\nOne application brings relier.\nat all druggists\nScad Free Sample at Ointment to\nHmnphreys* Homco. Medicine Company\n156 William Street, Now Vork.\nSICK STOCK\nBOOK on treatment of Horses, Cows,\nSheep, Dogs and other animals, cent\nfree. Humphreys' Homeopathic Vet\nerinary Medicines, 156 William St, N. Y\nto use their influence in holding down\n\"wildcat\" speculation in the oil fields.\nMuch Money Wasted.\n\"A large part of the money no%v be\ning spent by Montana people iiu the oil\nfields is hopelessly wasted because peo\nple are regarding the oil fields as a\ngambling proposition rather than a legit\nimate business venture,\" asserted Mr.\nPeters. \"The real productive fields so\nfar have largely been bought by inter\nests outside the state because people\nhave not thoroughly investigated the\noil projects.\"\nOptimism for the future of Great\nFalls despite the present financial de\npression ,was tlh! keynote of the talk\ngiven by Sam Stephenson, president of\nthe First National bank. The outlook\nfor Great Falls, he said, is such as\nwould justify the starting of many bus\niness enterprises here.\nSees Lower Rates.\nThat a lower and more equitable\nfreight rate for shippers in Montana\nwill be secured was the prediction of\nF. J. Gies. chairman of the traffic com\nmittee of the Commercial club. As soon\nas the railroads have been restored to\nthe normal state under private owner\nship, he said, it is almost certain that\naction will be taken by them to lower\nthe freight rates in Montana.\nShirley Ford, speaking for the Mon\ntana Livestock Pavilion corporation,\npredicted that the maintenance of the\npavilion in Great Falls will eventually\nmean a (*r<\u00eest asset to the city by\nbringing stockmen of the state here\ntc sell their farm animals. The cor\nporation in assured of maintenance of\nthe pavilion here for the next two\nyears, he declared.\nWants College Here.\nAn appeal for a movement to get\na state college for Great Falls was the\nfeature of the address of the Rev.\nL. L. Totten, pastor of the First Pres\nbyterian church. He declared that the\nco-operation of the people of. Great\nFalls with the 11 Protestant churches\nwhich have started a movement for a\nnew college in the state would almost\ninsure thp founding of a coilpge here\nas the center of high school population\nis near Great Falls.\nThe final talk before the announce\nmen of the successful candidates for\ndirectors was made by Judge L. L.\nCallaway, chairman of the Commer\ncial club irrigation committee. The\ngreat asset of the state. Judge Calla\nway said,\" is its agriculture which can\nnot be developed to the highest de\ngree without irrigation. He declared,\nhowever, that hp was strongly oppos\ned to damming lakes in the national\nparks to furnish water for irrigation\nprojects. The natural beauties of the\nstate, he said, are also great assets\nend must be conserved forever.\nTHINKS HIS BUICK\nMADE CANADA TRIP\nLeRoy Johnson firings Car\nStripped of Tires Home\nFrom Vaughn.\nThat his Buick roadster, stolen from\nin front of the Elmore apartments\nMonday night, made a round trip to\nCanada before 1 it was abandoned near\nVaughn Thursday night is the belief\nof Le Roy Johnson, manager of the\nAlcazar theater.\n\"The car bad a full gasoline tank\nwhen I got it, and there were only\nthree or four quarts in it Monday,\"\nsaid Mr. Johnson. \"It was piled up\nin a ditch a mile and a half this side\nof Vaughn, just off what is known as\n'bootleggers' trail.'\n\"The car was stripped of every de\ntachable article, not only the spare\ntire being gone but the tires taken off\nthe wheels. I do not believe the men\nwho took the car did this, though. I\nam of the opinion that others who\npassed it after it had been abandoned\nwere responsible for the petty\nthievery.\"\nTHE NIGHTLY LINE\nTeacher\u2014\"What, Oscar, is the An\ncient Order of the Bath?\"\nYoung Oscar (puzzled)\u2014\"I dunno;\nJohnny usually comes first, then Wil\nlie, then the baby.\"\u2014Life.\nYOUNG'S SPECIALS\n$1.00\nNew shipment of White Voile Waists.\nsizes 36 to 46, each\nBungalow Aprons, Knit Petticoats, Medium \u00a34 <t Q\nWeight Union Suits. Special #1 I v\nNEW PRICES ON CORSETS\nCorsets formerly $2.25,\nnow\nCorsets up to $2.75,\nnow\nCorsets at $4.50,\nnow\nSpecial lot of Odd Numbers.\nSpecial\nSpecial lot of Fancy and Brocaded\nCorsets, values to $5.50, now\n$1.75\n$1.05\n$3.50\n$2.95\n$3.95\nNEW CHILDREN'S COATS\nJust received a new shipment of Children's Winter Coats;\nsizes 8 to 16; special \u20ac\"7 OC\nvalues at $12.75, $8.7$ and \u00abP I *90\nLadies Winter Coats,\nnow\n$14.75\nT. N. YOUNG\nThe Reliable Store\n,426 Central Avenue\nCONTEST MADE\n10 GET LOWER\nFREIGHT RATES\nCommercial Club Traffic De\npartment Puts in Busy\nYear in 1920.\nAccomplishments of the traffic de\npartment of the Great Falls Commer\ncial club, in co -operation with the\nother agencies with which it has\n\u00a3vorked, during 1920 were outlined in\nthe annual report by H. R. Schiffer,\ntraffic manager, at the club's annual\nmeeting. He said:\n\"The traffic department of the\nGreat Falls Commercial club during\n1920, was conducted under the au\nspices of its traffic committee, com\nposed of eight of the leading business\nmen of the city, F. J. Gies being the\nchairman. This committee has been\nin cession from one to three times\neach month regarding traffic matters\nand conditions affecting Great Falls\nand its surrounding territory.^\n\"This department has continued, as\nin the past, to bring before its mem\nbers any radical changes in freight\nrates, rules and regulations affecting\nthis territory and to exert itself in\nbringing new industries to the city; it\nhas also built up a first class tariff\nfile and is ready at all times to quote\nrates, routing and any other informa\ntion on traffic matters.\n\"The year just closed finds the end\nof government control of the railroads.\nDuring the past few years while the\nrailroads have been under government\noperation, this department has found\nit almost impossible to have any rates\nreadjusted in order to remove the\ngreat barriers that are now placed\nagainst this territory, and hopes that\nthe ensuing year will bring better re\nsults in traffic conditions.\n\"During 1920 the traffic depart\nment was concerned with the follow\ning important subjects:\nRepresentation at Washington.\n\"On February 28 congress passed\nthe Cummins-Esch bill known as the\ntransportation bill of 1920, which ter\nminates the end of government con\ntrol of the railroads. This bill gives\nthe Interstate Commerce Commission\nauthority to fix rates and charges so\nas to net the carriers five and one\nhalf per cent on a certain valuation\nto be fixed by the commission. On\nMarch 22, 23 and 24 of this year, the\ninterstate commerce commission held\nhearings in Washington. D. C.. with\nthe shipping public, railway officials\nand other organizations with a view\nto ascertaining how the country should\nbe divided into rate making groups,\nwhat valuation should be allowed the\nrailroads to base the five and one\nhalf per cent dividend aud what in\ncrease in ratfs would be necessary\nto protect the five and one-half per\ncent as allowed by the transportation\nact of 1920. The Great Falls Com\nmercial club was represented at these\nhearings to ask for the division of\nthe country into at least three groups\n\u2014eastern, southern and western, with\na possible subdivision of the western\ngroup, and to fight against any in\ncrease in freight rates which might be\nbased on a percentage basis as an\nincrease of this kind would only put\nan additional burden on this alreadv\nhigh rated territory. On July 28 the\ninterstate commerce commission gave\na decision on the above hearings that\nthe United States would be divided\ninto four groups for rate making pur\nposes\u2014official, southern, western and\nmountain Pacific groups.\n\"The official group will include all\nterritory east of Chicago and north of\nthe Mason-Dixon line. The rates in\nthis territory will be increased 40 per\ncent.\n\"The southern group will include all\nterritory south of the Mason-Dixon\nline and in this territory the rates will\nbe increased 25 per cent.\n\"The western group will include all\nterritory west of Chicago to the west\nern boundaries of the Dakotas and\nstraight south to the western boun\ndaries of Texas. In this territory the\nrates will be increased 35 per cent.\n\"The Mountain Pacific group, which\nincludes all territory west of the west\nern group, will have an increased rate\nof 25 per cent. On shipments moving\nfrom one group to another, the rates\nwill be increased 33 1-3 per cent.\n\"All passenger fares, excess bag\ngage rates and milk and cream rates\nwill be increased 2 0 pe r cent. All\npullman charges sucfi^as parTor car\ntickets and berths will be increased 50\nper cent. The Montana railway com\nmission allowed the Montana inter\nstate freight rates to be incresaed 25\n(Continued on Page Eight.)\nCLUB OPPORTUNITIES IN 1921\nPOINT ED BV RETIRIN G HEAD\nIrrigation, Highway Development, Aviation\nField and City Club Some Enterprises\nWhich Might Be Fostered.\nIrrigation,, highway development, an\naviation field, encouragement of man\nufactories, the institution of a city\nclub, an auditorium and greater inter\nest in such institutions as the Y. M.\nC. A., the Salvation Army and the\nItod Cross, were named by O. S.\nWarden, the retiring president, in his\naddress as matters which the Com\nmerial club might well take up during\nthe coming year.\nMr. Warden said:\n\"The Great Falls Commercial club\nis a little more than 30 years old.\nIt whs an infant when the now retir\ning president came to Great Falls.\nIt has changed its name several times.\nIt has seen periods of prosperity and\n\u2022lays of adversity. Since the year\n1914. it has been able to finish each\nfiscal period without indebtedness and\nready for new effort, and this is the\nease at the close of the 1920 period.\nThe percentage of Commercial club\u00bb\nthat have been able to maintain such\nrecord during the trying war period\nis quite small. There is, therefore,\nconsiderable cause for congratulation\nRt the present moment.\nWork of Club Never Ends\n\"The work of a commercial club\nnever ends. Each retiring president\nand board of directors leave many\nthings undone. There are always\nmore tasks 'o .^o than there are work\ners or available funds supporting the\ncontinuous effort of the secretary nnd\nhis associates. Commercial clubs\nmake mistakes because they are hu\nman. They are often criticized even\n.after they do the best they can.\nMany activities, either in qnmtity or\nkind that\u00ab are d'spleasing to some\npeople in any particular, are hailed\nand applauded as rather wonderful\nachievements in later years, when the\nfull fruition of the effort has boon\nworked out. There is never a cause\nfor real discouragement. The princi\npal rewards of commercial club work\nare within the satisfaction of h^vinc\ntried to serve the commim-ty well It\nis all in the game of building a citv.\nAt the close of a somewhat difficult\nyear. T wish to sincerelv thank the\nmembershin and the directors been use\nmany of the^( harp resoonded to nften\nrepeated calls for assistance with a\nhelnful loyaltv that canno* b\u00ab too\nhighly praised. There would he no\nexcuse to use further time except per\nhaps to indicate hrieflv whip of tli\"\nsuerestiors to which T think the in\ntention of the club mav wisely he\ndirected during the year 1921.\nTo Aid Civic Enterprises.\n\"The Commercial club ought, now\nthat the war is over, to take a rather\nmore intimate interest in the work\nof the other purely civic organizations\nof the city, such as the Y. M. C- A.,\nthe Salvation Army and the American\nRed Cross. Business method, I be- i\niieve. should be quite thoroughly intro-\nduced. Drives should be done away j\nwith. These associations should be i\nput entirely upon a supporting mem- j\nbership basis and their budgets kept\nwithin the money that is pledged be-\nfore it is expended. All of the out-\nstanding indebtedness of these organ\nizations ought, to wiped out as soon\nas general financial conditions inay\nwarrant such efforts. Routine activi-*\nties should be so arranged that they\nw^Il not overlap- This much can easi\nly be brought about by conference and\nfriendly co-operation.\n\"The irrigation of the lands that can\nbe put under r.-ater within the trade\nradius of Great Falls should further\nand continually engaee the attention\nof our Commercial club because each\nacre made productive adds so much to\nU. S. ARMY\nINSPECTED\nBACON\n12-lb. can ....$3.25\nWHERE\nQUALITY\nTELLS\nAND\nPRICE\nSELLS\nU. S. INSPECTED\nARMY\nCORNED BEEF\nNo. 2 cans 40<^\n2 cans tor 75\u00a3\nU. S. ARMY GOODS STORE\nAND OTHER MERCHANDISE\nOpposite Park Hotel 107 '/2 Central Avenue\nU. S. Army Regulation Wool Shirts, new, price .$4.50\nU. S. Renovated Shirts, like new $2.75 and $3.25\nU. S. Mess Pans 75$\nU. S. Canteens 75<C\nU. S. Khaki Breeches ....98.25\n(J. S. Wool Breeches $3 to $4.50\nSpiral Puttees ....$1.25 to 92\nSlip-oil Sweaters, all wool, 93.25\nU. S. Army Old lissue\nGray Wool Blankets 95.00\nU. S. Olive Drab Wool Blankets,\nsize 6Sx80, renovated, but all per\nfect and like new 95.SO\n[J. S. Duffle or Laundry Bags 10<*\nIT. S. S. B. Woolen Plaid Blankets,\ndouble, size (K\u00abS0. Elegant blan\nket for home use ..88.5\u00a9\nU. S. M. C. Jumpers 92.00\nU. S. Regulation Wool Underwear\n$2.25\nLEATHER COATS\nSelling below manufacturer's cost, Mackinaw and three\nquarter lengths, reversible, imported wool tweed and gab\nardine linings. Prices $27.50 to $45.00\nAlso\u2014Coveralls, Socks, Soap Boxes, Tooth Brushes, Stag\nShirts, Webb Belts, Gloves, Overalls, Pillows, Etc.\nHerman's\nKamous U. S.\nArmy Drass\nShoes\n97.25\nMall\nOrders\nFilled.\nInquiries\nSolicited.\nLeather Vests\nVarious Styles,\nSelling for One-Half\nRegular Priocs\n97.50 to 912.00\nEDMONSON'S\nDENTAL SPECIALISTS\nAre prepared to care for all tootb and gum ailments in the most mod\nern way known to dental science at moderate fees\nX-RAY EQUIPMENT\nThe Most Modern Offices in the West\nDR. E. E. EDMONSON, DENTIST\nOver Lap\u00e8yre's Drug Store Entrance on Third Street South\ni\n\nj\ni\nj\n\n\n\n\nthe abiding commercial strength of\ncommunity. The. Montana Irrigation\nInstitute is proposing a new irriga\ntion code for the consideration of the\nlegislature that has just convened\nThis is perhaps the greatest single\nkind of work we ,<an push along in\nt ie immediate future. The appropria\ntions for government projects need to\nbe followed with earnest solicitation\nHighway Development Urged.\n\"For six years, this city, working\nwith the other Montana towns, has\nbeen helping and perhaps leading the\nway in urging the development of the\nso-called Y-G Bee line highway from\nYellowstone National park to Glacier\nIVational park. Happily, what has\nbeen accomplished resulted during the\nlast year in definitely placing Great\nFalls\" upon the master highway that\nis proposed connecting all of the prin\ncipal national parks of North America.\n\"We ought to continue to co-operate\nwith those who are pushing this import\nant enterprise. There is cause for\ngratification that the opening of the\nyean 1921 sees seventy-five miles of\ngravel road extending from one end of\nCascade county to the other, complete\nand ready for use. A survey is now\nbeing made to see if we can build an\nadequate highway through the Missouri\nriver canyon from Cascade to Craig on\nthe thoroughfare leading to the city of\nHelena. This subject will require fur\nther consideration as soon as the sur\nvey is finished. The cutticig of trans\nportation costs and distance between\nthe two important cities of Great Falls\nand Helena is a project that may re\nquire time for completion but which has\nan importance that we cannot well af\nford to disregard. We will be acting\nwisely if efforts continue until a good\nroad has been arranged over the Hlack\nfoot Indian reservation and on into\nGlacier park. Two other roads per\nhaps are of equal importance\u2014a high\nway through Roosevelt Pass from Gla\ncier park to Belton aud one across the\ndivide inside the park which, of .-ourse,\nis under the jurisdiction of. and will be\nbuilt by the national government. '1 he\nmountains ought to be cut by another\nroad built from the 1 Aversion dam of\nthe Nun River Reclamation project on\nover the mountains and into the re\nonreeful country west of the divide.\nThis construction would probably be\ndone by uniting other funds with those\nof the forest reserve.\nAuto Camp Site Established.\n\"A committee from *he Commercial\nclub during the last year persuaded the\ncity council and the i ark board to he\ngin the work of establishing a city camp\nsite to be maintained during Ihe sum\nmer. These sites have become an ex\npected advantage to outing tourist tiav\nelers and a benefit t(j the towns in\nwhich they are located. Some fm-ther\ninvestment, though .not a lirge one,\nwill be require^ in 1921 to complete\nthe Great Falls camp site. We should\ntake, 1 think, a more helpful interest\nin the routine work that the park board\nis doing to beautify the city.\n\"A properly arranged aviation field\nwill soon be required in every town\nof commercial importance. The in\nvestigation of this subject, already be\ngun. can be easily completed in the\nnear future.\n\"Negotiations have been going for\nward during the last few months lock\ning to the better connecting of county\nroads with city streets so that we\nmay have more harmonious and ade\nquate approaches to the city. These\nefforts ought to go forward without\ninterruption.\nNew Industries Possible\n\"In the years since the beginning of\nthe world war, financial conditions\nhave prevented the bringing in of\nmany_ important contemplated new in\ndustries to help build up the city. In\nthe meantime, however, a standardi\nzation of hours and wages have been\nworking in our favor. There are\nmany who believe that wool\u00ab 11 mills\nand tann\u00e9ries could prosper in Mon\ntana -whenever there is money avail\nable for investment in new enterprises.\nIron and steel will soon largely utilize\nour water power. I think consider\nable investigation of possible indus\ntries can be carried on during the pres\nent year. I hope that we may enter\nupon new realization along this line\nwhenever we get to the end of the\npresent liquidation period.\n\"Early in last year, a stock sales\npavulion for the use of this city and\nall of Montana was brought to com\npletion. It i\u00ab,a foundation stone that\ncan be built upon. There is an ambition\non the part of those that are inter\nested to develop this pavillion until\nwe are able to establish an annual\nstock show in the existing northwest\nern circuit. Our business people. I\nam sure, wish to see this done as noon\nas the situation warrants such ex\npenditure. Stock raising will come\nback to its old and to greater pros\nperity in Montana. There should be\na renewed interest in dairying now.\nCity Has No City Club.\n\"I wish to mention two other things\nwhich cannot be worked out at present\nbut which should not be lost sight of:\n\"A return of prosperity will soon\nemphasize the need of a city club. The\nabsence of such a social center often\ncauses unfavorable comment. This in\nstitution will probably have to wait\nuntil its twin sister, the country club,\nis thoroughly financed and completed.\nTentative plans for a city club were\ndiscussed a few years ago but had to\nbe put aside for the taking up of other\nand more pressing community burdens.\n\"I realize that many conservative\nheads will shake as the subject of a\nmemorial auditorium is approached at\nthis time. Such a desired addition to\nthe public improvements of the city\nwas given considerable attention by the\nCommercial club during the administra\ntion of Grant Call. The investigation\nthen made will be of value when the\nsubject is again taken up. I thinK that\nthe first reasonable year of prosper\nity should find us earnestly working for\na municipal auditorium. Considerable\nstudy of our needs and the general\nsituation leads to a conclusion that a\nbuilding, should develop about as fol\nlows: This structure should possess\narchitectural beauty. It should be\nbuilt from the proceeds of the sale of\nmunicipal bonds. It should comfortably\nseat an audience of four thousand anil\nthe highest utility requires that it be\nlocated close to the business center. I\nwould urge that under its roof be ar\nranged a Charles M. Russell art gal\nlery and historical museum. One of\nthese features would do honor to the\nnow almost world renowned frontier j\nartist who is a long time resident of i\nthe city. The other would enable the i\npreservation of many historical relics j\nof northern Montana which are now\nbeing lost as the shadows lengthen for\nthe pioneer. I would put into this i\nauditorium a fine community organ. I\ni his organ as well as the furnishings\nfor the art gallery and the museum\ncould be supplied by popular subscrip-\nSaturday, January 15, 1921\nA Remarkable Special Purchase of 60\nFashionable Serge Dresses\nA Break in the Market Brings Big Bargain to You\nValues\nto\n$39.75\n12.50\nValues\nto\n$39.75\nOur New York buyer found conditions in the market below\nnormal, manufacturers anxious to dispose of their stocks at almost\nany price\u2014glad to be rid of their surplus for even less than actual\ncost of the materials. He was able to secure 60 unusually pretty\ndresses at enormous reductions, dresses that formerly sold as high\nas $39.75. The savings will revert to you in this sale as all th e s e\ndresses without exception are now offered at only. .$12.50 each\nWomen's Dress Shoes\nBlack and brown calf and black\nkid skfo shoes; odd\npairs, now only\n$4.98\nMen's Work Shoes\nBlack and brown work shoes; all\nsizes in the lot.\nNow only\n$3.98\nChildren's Button Shoes\nFine black kidskin shoes; former\nly $2.49 and $2.98. \u00bb4 AA\nNow only 9 ivO\nBoys' Overalls\nOf blue, fast color denim. QQ\u00ab%\nNow only wOv\nMen's Canvas Gloves\nHeavy knitted wrist, warm S-oz.\nfleeced canvas, 4 O'/ \u00ee\u00e2\nper pair I V\nGeorgette and Crepe de\nChine Blouses\n$3.49\n\u2014former values to $7.93; flesh snd